key_insights: Scaling laws appear as a strong recurring isomorphism across stats, CS, and materials science
Quantum-classical hybrid optimization is genuinely reused across logistics and genomics
Convergence theory provides strong mathematical bridges between physics and pure math
Neural network mentions create some false positives when used generically
Diffusion can mean different things (generative models vs physical diffusion) - source of false positives
Emergence patterns appear in both biological/neural and physical systems
Strategic behavior isomorphisms cross political science, economics, and finance
false_positive_patterns: Generic 'neural network' mentions without specific structural mechanisms
Diffusion in generative models vs diffusion in physics (different meanings)
'Optimization' mentioned but with very different mathematical frameworks
recommendations: Add context-aware filtering: 'diffusion model' vs 'heat diffusion'
Require stronger structural overlap beyond mechanism type matching
Weight shared technical terms more heavily (e.g., 'quantum-classical', 'scaling law')
Filter out matches where only generic methodological terms overlap (e.g., just 'neural network')
Current 60% precision is good but could reach 70-80% with these improvements
